properties.pdescrip: Reconnaissance geochemistry of the southwestern North American porphyry copper province in eastern California, Arizona, New Mexico, and western Texas.
properties.pkeyword: beryllium; bismuth; manganese; tin; tungsten; study areas; critical minerals; geochemistry
properties.abstract: The southwestern North American porphyry copper province stretches across eastern California, Arizona, New Mexico, and western Texas, and comprises one of the world’s largest endowments of copper. The tectonics and magmatism during the late Cretaceous to the early Paleogene across the southwest has provided a fertile environment for hosting magmatic and hydrothermal systems that host abundant mineralization. There are numerous historic mines and prospects that have not been thoroughly analyzed for more than the target metallic assays. We now recognize that these systems host more than the initial metal resource target and can host critical mineral constituents as well. The New Mexico Bureau of Geology and Mineral Resources in collaboration with the Arizona State Geological Survey, California Geological Survey, and Texas Bureau of Economic Geology is conducting a project that will accomplish the following related tasks: 1) compilation of existing geochemical data; 2) definition of sampling methods; 3) sample collection from porphyry occurrences and other selected sites for system-scale detailed work; 4) sample characterization (petrography, whole rock geochemistry, mineral chemistry, microanalysis, geo/thermochronology, geobarometry, computed tomography, fluid inclusions, etc.); 5) compilation of legacy and new data into a uniform geochemical database; 6) writing up comprehensive summary report on the critical mineral potential for individual prospects/deposits and within specific alteration types/rock types. The objectives of this collaborative project are: 1) to provide a rigorous compilation of geochemical analyses (both new and legacy data) with an emphasis on which specific porphyry systems have elevated concentrations of critical minerals; and 2) to develop a better understanding of the distribution of critical minerals within the alteration haloes of porphyry systems. This project aligns with Earth MRI by providing integrated geologic and geochemical data that can be applied to mapping, development of geospatial resource data, and generating mineral resources data for a regionally mineralized province. Potential critical minerals in the project area: Be, Bi, Mn, Sn, W.
